<isis lang="en">
    <stitle>ELECTRICAL SYSTEM TROUBLESHOOTING GUIDE - 9200, 9300, 9400 Models Built After January 1, 1995 - ELECTRICAL
        TROUBLESHOOTING CATERPILLAR 3176B AND 3406E ELECTRONIC ENGINES - DIAGNOSTICS AND TROUBLESHOOTING - IMPORTANT
        STEPS BEFORE TESTING
    </stitle>
    <svcman/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="proctype" graphiccount="0">
        <title>IMPORTANT STEPS BEFORE TESTING</title>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">
                <emph type="bold">Gather information</emph>by talking to the driver if possible. Try to determine the
                exact symptoms by gathering relevant information:
            </para>
            <randlist type="bullet">
                <item>
                    <para>What happened, and when?</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>Under what conditions?</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>When did the symptoms begin?</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>What else occurred at that time?</para>
                </item>
            </randlist>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">
                <emph type="bold">Verify the problem</emph>. Is the complaint due to mis-understood customer selected
                parameters? Use Prolink EST to review customer selected parameters.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">
                <emph type="bold">Check for and record</emph>any logged fault codes.
            </para>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Do the logged codes correlate to probable causes?</para>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Were the codes logged about the same time as the symptoms appeared? Were the codes
                    logged repeatedly?
                </para>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Are the logged codes related to other symptoms? Do they have a common cause?</para>
            </step2>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">
                <emph type="bold">Avoid Preconceived Ideas!</emph>Eliminate any non-electrical causes for the problem
                first (contaminated fuel, clogged air filters etc.).
            </para>
        </step1>
    </svcproc>
